From 439ef9a058e19ae1abbc7032155459249300b091 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Nadia Chambers <nadia.yvette.chambers@ik.me>
Date: Wed, 27 May 2026 18:06:40 +0200
Subject: [PATCH 126/174] alpha: define __pte_val_to_phys (inverse of
 __phys_to_pte_val)
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Alpha stores the hardware PFN in PTE bits[63:32], and defines
__phys_to_pte_val(phys) = ((phys >> MMUPAGE_SHIFT) << 32) but never
provided the inverse.  The generic identity fallback in
include/linux/pgtable.h returns the raw PTE value, so pte_suboffset()
extracts garbage on alpha (flag bits 12..17 rather than the actual
sub-PAGE bits that live up at bits 12..17 of the *physical* address
encoded in PFN bits[63:32]).

PGCL's COW path (e.g. do_wp_page → wp_page_copy after commit
0e8705ff95d8) calls pte_suboffset(orig_pte) to preserve the source
PTE's sub-PAGE offset when remapping a COWed page; on alpha the wrong
sub-PAGE was being used, so the new PTE pointed at the wrong MMUPAGE
of the new folio and userspace read uninitialised content from the
fresh copy.  At PGCL=6 with init(1) starting from a glibc/busybox
binary this manifests as an endless userspace unaligned-access trap
loop with the trap PC pinned to one instruction — the loaded code is
zeroes and the instruction at the entry point decodes to an aligned
load of an unaligned operand.

The inverse: mask out flag bits with _PFN_MASK, then shift down by
(32 - MMUPAGE_SHIFT) so the MMUPAGE-PFN lands at bit position
MMUPAGE_SHIFT and the result reads as a normal physical byte address.

Verified clean on alpha PGCL=6: pgcl-stress 12/0, LTP 74p/0f/27s.

Signed-off-by: Nadia Yvette Chambers <nadia.yvette.chambers@gmail.com>
---
 arch/alpha/include/asm/pgtable.h | 1 +
 1 file changed, 1 insertion(+)

diff --git a/arch/alpha/include/asm/pgtable.h b/arch/alpha/include/asm/pgtable.h
index 20c79f48fc4c..0664308899c6 100644
--- a/arch/alpha/include/asm/pgtable.h
+++ b/arch/alpha/include/asm/pgtable.h
@@ -197,6 +197,7 @@ extern struct page *empty_zero_page_struct;
 #define PFN_PTE_SHIFT		32
 #define pte_pfn(pte)		((pte_val(pte) >> PFN_PTE_SHIFT) >> PAGE_MMUSHIFT)
 #define __phys_to_pte_val(phys)	(((phys) >> MMUPAGE_SHIFT) << 32)
+#define __pte_val_to_phys(val)	(((val) & _PFN_MASK) >> (32 - MMUPAGE_SHIFT))
 
 #define pte_page(pte)	pfn_to_page(pte_pfn(pte))
 
